    16	## Current Increment
    17	
    18	### iscsi-tool-lab-vhdx-operator-selection
    19	
    20	- Status: `active`
    21	- Owner: `powershell-pair-coder`
    22	- Goal: let the operator choose a discovered Lab child and parent VHDX entry, while keeping creation and iSCSI publication out of scope
    23	
    24	## Hotfix Track
    25	
    26	### bugfix
    27	
    28	- Status: `merged`
    29	- Head checkpoint: `3758619`
    30	- Base checkpoint: `daf202d`
    31	- Goal: harden HQ-local identity restore when `LocalAccounts` cmdlets cannot see or manage existing local SAM principals on the guest
    32	
    33	### Current Progress
    34	
    35	- Active development lives under `app/`
    36	- Increment 3 is complete and tagged as `configure-hq-increment-3`
    37	- Increment 4 now has real code and tests for:
    38	  - managed role ACL definitions and NTFS ACL orchestration helpers
    39	  - required HQ principal definitions for mirrored users, ACL groups, and `HQ\svc_lab`
    40	  - guest-side principal state export and wrapper entrypoint via `-ExportSecurityPrincipalState`
    41	  - create-or-detect handling for missing required HQ users and groups
    42	  - required group membership handling for existing HQ users
    43	  - optional identity restore during activation via `-RunIdentityRestore`
    44	  - ACL application inside activation after the final workflow rows are built
    45	  - saved-state cleanup planning for added group links and principals
    46	  - explicit identity cleanup via `-RunIdentityCleanup`, including link removal, planned-removal review, and confirmed user and group deletion in one pass
    47	  - comment-first cleanup so intent comments sit on the exact code and tests they describe
    48	- The Hyper-V host `P50` is not joined to `HQ`, so ACL and SMB policy must be authored in terms of HQ-local principals rather than `P50\...` identities
    49	- WSL2 access from `P50` is expected to arrive through an SMB session authenticated with HQ-local credentials
    50	- Latest increment-4 checkpoint is commit `daf202d` tagged as `configure-hq-increment-4`
    51	- The merged bugfix track on `dev` includes refreshed post-activation drive-letter discovery, stricter stale-ADSI cleanup planning, tolerant duplicate-create handling for hidden existing principals, and restore-time hidden-local-SAM verification
    52	- Guest reruns and the finished SMB closeout established a clean handoff into a separate iSCSI tool boundary
    53	- A new design-only iSCSI note now defines how an optional block publication mode would work for a writable child VHDX while keeping the parent VHDX read-only
    54	- A dedicated iSCSI test file now exists at `app/tests/configure_hq.iscsi.Tests.ps1`
    55	- `Get-HqLabVhdDiscoveryChoices` is implemented and returns both child and parent choice sets with `CreateNew` defaults plus discovered `UseExisting` VHDX entries
    56	- `configure_hq.ps1` already exposes the standalone discovery entrypoint through `[switch]$DiscoverLabVhdChoices`
    57	- The dedicated iSCSI Pester file has been run against the current tree and is green with `Passed: 1 Failed: 0`
    58	- The discovery increment is therefore complete at the verified helper-and-switch boundary
    59	- The next active slice is now limited to:
    60	  - mapping discovered child and parent choice rows into an operator-facing selection flow
    61	  - preserving the existing create-new placeholders without creating folders or VHDX files yet
    62	  - returning the selected choice objects cleanly for a later execution or publication step
    63	- This next slice still does not create folders, create VHDX files, or publish iSCSI targets
    64	- Historical SMB and increment-2 checkpoints remain available for lineage and rollback analysis
    65	
    66	### QA Reading
    67	
    68	- Tags: `ready-for-red`, `risk-identified`, `needs-criteria`
    69	- Commentary: the discovery helper and standalone discovery switch are already present and verified green. The next smallest slice is no longer another execution switch; it is the operator-selection boundary that consumes the discovered child and parent choice rows without widening into create or publish behavior.
    70	- Next steps:
    71	  - write the next failing test for operator selection over discovered child and parent choices
    72	  - keep the selection contract narrow and return structured selected rows rather than performing creation or publication
    73	  - preserve `-DiscoverLabVhdChoices` as the non-destructive inspection path
    74	- Quality risks:
    75	  - real share enumeration may expose folder-layout or naming variations beyond the first discovery test
    76	  - the Windows iSCSI target support boundary for publishing a differencing child disk is still unverified
    77	  - selection UX may drift into creation or publication logic unless the slice boundary stays explicit
    78	
    79	### Blockers
    80	
    81	- no blocker prevents the operator-selection slice itself
    82	- the iSCSI publication path is intentionally split into a separate upcoming tool and still needs its own implementation plan
    83	- the later iSCSI publication path still depends on validating the Windows differencing-disk support boundary
    84	
    85	### Open Questions
    86	
    87	- Resolved: use `V:\VHDs\disks\sharedisk.vhdx` as the `ShareDrive` VHD path.
    88	- Resolved: guest activation consumes a host-generated metadata module instead of relying only on guest-visible heuristics.
    89	- Resolved: manual VM selection replaces auto-detection as the preferred host workflow.
    90	- Resolved: increment 3 ends at dedup execution, missing-feature handling, and execution-mode guarding.
    91	- Resolved: increment 4 will use HQ-local groups plus `HQ\svc_lab` instead of abstract domain groups or `Everyone`.
    92	- Resolved: WSL2 access from `P50` will be modeled through HQ-authenticated SMB sessions rather than direct `P50\...` principals.
    93	- Resolved: the standalone discovery switch already exists as `-DiscoverLabVhdChoices`.
    94	- Open: should operator selection use index-based choice input, path-based choice input, or support both in the first slice?
